Reports: Radiology Report: The chest X-ray image shows a right-sided pneumothorax. A pneumothorax is a condition where air accumulates in the pleural space, which is the area between the lung and the chest wall. This can cause the lung to collapse, leading to difficulty breathing and chest pain. In this case, the pneumothorax is located on the right side of the chest.

Radiology Report: The chest X-ray image shows a large right-sided pleural effusion. A pleural effusion is an abnormal accumulation of fluid in the pleural space, which is the area between the layers of tissue that line the lungs and the chest cavity. This can be caused by various conditions, such as infections, heart failure, or malignancies. Further evaluation and tests will be needed to determine the exact cause and appropriate treatment for the patient.

Radiology Report: The chest X-ray image shows a large mass in the right hemithorax. This mass is causing a mediastinal shift, which means that the structures within the mediastinum, the central compartment of the thoracic cavity, are being pushed or displaced due to the presence of the mass. The mediastinum contains important structures such as the heart, major blood vessels, and the trachea. A mediastinal shift can potentially lead to complications and may require further evaluation and treatment.
